<subSubSection pageId="9" pageNumber="572" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1436,412,727]" pageId="9" pageNumber="572">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,345,484,510]" pageId="9" pageNumber="572">Distribution</emphasis>
. Tropical and temperate waters of the Atlantic, tropical water of the Indian Ocean, and in part of the Pacific, in SE of 
<collectingCountry box="[380,447,521,547]" name="Japan" pageId="9" pageNumber="572">Japan</collectingCountry>
, S of 
<collectingCountry box="[508,661,520,547]" name="New Zealand" pageId="9" pageNumber="572">New Zealand</collectingCountry>
, and in the eastern tropics (
<bibRefCitation author="Vinogradov, M. E. &amp; Volkov, A. F. &amp; Semenova, T. N." box="[962,1224,520,547]" pageId="9" pageNumber="572" refId="ref14930" refString="Vinogradov, M. E., Volkov, A. F. &amp; Semenova, T. N. (1996) Hyperiid amphipods (Amphipoda, Hyperiidea) of the world oceans. Smithsonian Institution Libraries, Siegel-Causey, D., Scientific Editor, Washington D. C. and Oxonian Press Pvt. Ltd., New Delhi, 632 pp. [English translation of the 1982 Russian original]" type="book" year="1996">
Vinogradov 
<emphasis box="[1103,1151,520,546]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="572">et al</emphasis>
. 1996
</bibRefCitation>
). In the eastern Pacific it ranges from 
<geoCoordinate box="[372,431,557,583]" degrees="33" direction="north" orientation="latitude" pageId="9" pageNumber="572" precision="55555" value="33.0">33°N</geoCoordinate>
to 
<geoCoordinate box="[467,524,557,583]" degrees="20" direction="south" orientation="latitude" pageId="9" pageNumber="572" precision="55555" value="-20.0">20°S</geoCoordinate>
, including off the west coast of the Baja California Peninsula (
<bibRefCitation author="Shih, C. - T. &amp; Hendrycks, E. A." pageId="9" pageNumber="572" pagination="253 - 296" refId="ref14260" refString="Shih, C. - T. &amp; Hendrycks, E. A. (2003) A new species and new records of the genus Vibilia Milne Edwards, 1830 (Amphipoda: Hyperiidea: Vibiliidae) occurring in the eastern Pacific Ocean. Journal of Natural History, 37, 253 - 296. https: // doi. org / 10.1080 / 713834685" type="journal article" year="2003">Shih &amp; Hendrycks 2003</bibRefCitation>
, García Madrigal 2007) and in the Gulf of California (present study).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="9" pageNumber="572" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1436,412,727]" pageId="9" pageNumber="572">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,308,629,655]" pageId="9" pageNumber="572">Remarks</emphasis>
. This species was not recorded by 
<bibRefCitation author="Siegel-Causey, D." box="[713,958,628,655]" pageId="9" pageNumber="572" refId="ref14372" refString="Siegel-Causey, D. (1982) Factors determining the distribution of hyperiid Amphipoda in the Gulf of California. Ph. D. Thesis, University of Arizona, Tucson, Arizona, 535 pp." type="book" year="1982">Siegel-Causey (1982)</bibRefCitation>
in his Gulf of 
<collectingRegion box="[1131,1245,628,654]" country="United States of America" name="California" pageId="9" pageNumber="572">California</collectingRegion>
survey and only once during our survey. 
<bibRefCitation author="Shih, C. - T. &amp; Hendrycks, E. A." box="[424,715,664,691]" pageId="9" pageNumber="572" pagination="253 - 296" refId="ref14260" refString="Shih, C. - T. &amp; Hendrycks, E. A. (2003) A new species and new records of the genus Vibilia Milne Edwards, 1830 (Amphipoda: Hyperiidea: Vibiliidae) occurring in the eastern Pacific Ocean. Journal of Natural History, 37, 253 - 296. https: // doi. org / 10.1080 / 713834685" type="journal article" year="2003">Shih &amp; Hendrycks (2003)</bibRefCitation>
found it mostly in depth shallower than 
<quantity box="[1171,1245,664,691]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.5" pageId="9" pageNumber="572" unit="m" value="250.0">250 m</quantity>
, with one exception at 1253– 
<quantity box="[299,387,700,727]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.207" pageId="9" pageNumber="572" unit="m" value="1207.0">1207 m</quantity>
.
</paragraph>
